Research automated bug detection techniques that operate purely on static analysis without execution, focusing on patterns detectable at the AST level in Python, Java, JavaScript, TypeScript, Go, and Rust. Categorize the bug patterns by type: null/nil dereference patterns, resource leak patterns (unclosed files, connections, handles), exception swallowing (catching and ignoring exceptions), integer overflow and underflow, off-by-one errors in loop bounds, unreachable code, use before initialization, and API misuse (calling methods in wrong order or with wrong argument types). For each category, research which tools detect them (Infer, SpotBugs, FindBugs, Coverity, CodeQL) and what their false positive rates are on benchmarks. Research the Defects4J benchmark and how well static tools predict which bugs it contains. Cover the FindBugs/SpotBugs bug pattern taxonomy and how it has been extended and validated over time. Also research the specific bug patterns that are highly language-specific versus those that translate across languages — for example, Python's mutable default argument anti-pattern versus Java's equals/hashCode contract violation. Include research on machine learning approaches to bug detection: DeepBugs, code2vec for vulnerability detection, and whether ML approaches outperform traditional pattern-based detection on precision and recall with the same false positive budget.
